Forcing and Response\
\
\pard\tx566\tx1133\tx1700\tx2267\tx2834\tx3401\tx3968\tx4535\tx5102\tx5669\tx6236\tx6803\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 The climate system can be forced by external processes. For example, the Earth\'92s temperature is partly determined by the Sun\'92s energy output. This is a forcing. Changes in forcing are due to changes in the external processes. A change in the brightness of the Sun could produce, as a response, a change in the Earth\'92s temperature. \
\
We can capture this idea mathematically by writing that for a given change in radiative forcing, \\(\\Delta R\\), there will be a change in temperature, \\(\\Delta T\\), such that\
\
\\[\\lambda \\Delta R = \\Delta T \\; ,\\]\
\
where \\(\\lambda\\) is called the climate sensitivity parameter and it determines how strong the temperature response is for a given climate system (it turns out that Earth now, Earth during an ice age, Mars now, etc., all have different climate sensitivity parameters). This equation is a \'91linear\'92 equation and assumes that the change in forcing, \\(\\Delta R\\), is relatively small (the current energy imbalance due to global warming is about 1 \\(\\text\{W\}/\\text\{m\}^2\\), compared to the total energy flux of about 340 \\(\\text\{W\}/\\text\{m\}^2\\)). \
\
This equation works well for a planet with no atmosphere. But what if by changing the solar radiative forcing, the Earth\'92s atmosphere were to respond in some way? What if the atmosphere could counteract or damp the forcing? If the Sun were to put out more energy, perhaps the Earth\'92s atmosphere could change somehow to cool itself down so that it wouldn\'92t warm as much as it might otherwise do without an atmosphere? Alternatively, perhaps it\'92s possible for Earth\'92s atmosphere to amplify the increase in solar radiation, making Earth even hotter than it might otherwise be? These effects are called \'91feedbacks\'92 and they occur widely in many technical fields, and even in daily life. \'91Positive feedbacks\'92 amplify and \'91negative feedbacks\'92 regulate or damp.\
