\
The mass of water vapor in the atmosphere exceeds the mass of carbon dioxide by about a factor of 4, and water vapor contributes more to the downward infrared at the Earth\'92s surface than \\(\\text\{CO\}_2\\) does. Despite these facts, \\(\\text\{CO\}_2\\) plays a controlling role in the greenhouse effect, while water vapor plays a subservient role. The reason is that water vapor is condensible and can be removed from the atmosphere by precipitation, whereas \\(\\text\{CO\}_2\\) does not condense under conditions found in the Earth\'92s atmosphere.\
\
Lacis et al. (2010) illustrated the primary role of \\(\\text\{CO\}_2\\) through a clever and simple experiment with a climate model. When run with realistic present-day \\(\\text\{CO\}_2\\) concentrations, the model produces a realistic simulation of today\'92s observed climate. In the experiment, Lacis and colleagues removed all of the \\(\\text\{CO\}_2\\) (and other noncondensing greenhouse gases) from the atmosphere. The results were spectacular. The surface temperature began to fall immediately as a direct result of the absence of \\(\\text\{CO\}_2\\). This led to a reduction in the water vapor content of the atmosphere and additional cooling through the water vapor feedback. The positive snow and ice albedo feedback also reinforced the cooling. The dramatic results are shown in the figure below. Within 10 simulated years, the Earth approached an ice-covered state in which the frigid model atmosphere contained very little water vapor.\
\
